        {
          "id": "framework_not_finding",
          "label": "The primary deliverable is framed as a reusable framework or methodology, not solely as a binary finding that either works or doesn't"
        },
        {
          "id": "graceful_degradation",
          "label": "The aim's value is decoupled from any single component's performance \u2014 it retains value even if individual elements underperform"
        },
        {
          "id": "confident_flexibility",
          "label": "Language about contingencies and adaptability conveys intellectual maturity and preparedness rather than uncertainty or defensiveness"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 2
    },
    {
      "name": "Explicit Contrast and Displacement",
      "category": "Content",
      "description": "The writing must name what currently fills the space the proposed work will occupy \u2014 the specific incumbent approach, the existing workaround, the thing being replaced \u2014 and articulate why it falls short as a design flaw, not a resource problem. Contrasts must be named and landed, not gestured at or implied. Abstractions like 'current methods are inadequate' must be replaced with concrete descriptions of what those methods actually look like in practice.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "incumbent_named",
          "label": "The specific existing approach or workaround currently occupying the clinical/research slot is named concretely"
        },
        {
          "id": "structural_flaw",
          "label": "The incumbent's limitation is framed as a design or structural flaw, not merely a resource or effort gap"
        },
        {
          "id": "contrast_landed",
          "label": "The difference between the proposed approach and the incumbent is stated explicitly, not left for the reader to infer"
        },
        {
          "id": "prior_work_as_input",
          "label": "Existing literature and prior approaches are reframed as inputs to or foundations for the proposed work, not simply as competitors or failures"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 3
    },
    {
      "name": "Interdisciplinary Accessibility",
      "category": "Audience",
      "description": "Writing must be legible to reviewers from different disciplinary backgrounds \u2014 neuroscience, engineering, public health, clinical medicine \u2014 without dumbing down the science. Technical terms should be included for precision but paired with brief contextual cues (parentheticals, appositive definitions) so non-specialist reviewers can follow the argument without losing the thread. Specificity should serve clarity: naming exact instruments, protocols, or signals helps non-experts understand what's broken or proposed more than abstractions do.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "soft_landings",
          "label": "Discipline-specific terms are accompanied by brief contextual cues that allow non-specialist reviewers to continue reading without confusion"
        },
        {
          "id": "multi_audience_resonance",
          "label": "Key arguments address concerns that matter to different reviewer backgrounds \u2014 e.g., feasibility for engineers, clinical relevance for clinicians, scalability for public health"
        },
        {
          "id": "specificity_as_clarity",
          "label": "Concrete names of instruments, protocols, or signals are used in place of vague references, because specificity aids rather than hinders comprehension"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_assumed_expertise",
          "label": "No section assumes deep familiarity with a single discipline's methodology without providing enough context for a reviewer from another field"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 4
    },
    {
      "name": "Rhetorical Craft and Register Control",
      "category": "Style",
      "description": "Sentence rhythm, length variation, and register should be deliberately controlled to serve the argument's emotional arc. Closing lines must feel like arrivals \u2014 doors opening \u2014 not summaries or process descriptions. Temperature should sit between bold conviction and quiet confidence: speaking on behalf of patients and stakes, not pivoting to methodology vocabulary. Process language ('builds a platform,' 'enables detection') is treated as a register collapse when it follows urgency-driven prose.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "closing_as_arrival",
          "label": "Section and paragraph endings feel like promises or openings, not summaries or announcements of methodology"
        },
        {
          "id": "rhythm_variation",
          "label": "Sentence length and structure vary deliberately to control pacing \u2014 short sentences for impact, longer ones for building complexity"
        },
        {
          "id": "register_consistency",
          "label": "The prose maintains a consistent register throughout each section without collapsing from patient-centered urgency into bureaucratic or process language"
        },
        {
          "id": "temperature_calibration",
          "label": "Claims are bold enough to convey conviction but restrained enough to avoid sounding promotional or theatrical"
        },
        {
          "id": "structural_echoes",
          "label": "Key images or phrases introduced early are called back later, making the prose feel architecturally shaped rather than accumulated"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 5
    }
  ],
  "version": 2,
  "source": "criteria_classification",
  "writing_type": "NIH grant proposals (R01 and similar federal research funding applications)",
  "user_goals_summary": "This user writes grant proposals that build emotional and intellectual urgency through escalating narrative architecture, making reviewers feel the problem before encountering the proposed solution. They value extreme specificity \u2014 naming incumbents, naming what's displaced, naming the exact clinical reality \u2014 and they want every section to feel like a complete, independently valuable thought rather than a setup for what follows. Accessibility across disciplinary boundaries is essential, but never at the cost of scientific precision.",
  "coaching_notes": "This user has an unusually refined sense of narrative architecture in scientific writing \u2014 they think in terms of emotional arcs, not just information delivery. Their most consistent non-negotiable is that urgency must be *felt* by the reader, not merely stated; if a passage reads like a literature review or a factual catalogue, it has failed regardless of accuracy. They respond best when the assistant names specific craft choices and invites pressure-testing, and they are precise in distinguishing between what's 'working' and what's 'almost there.' When giving feedback, they often identify the exact sentence where momentum breaks \u2014 trust that specificity and revise surgically rather than rewriting broadly."
}

RECENT CONVERSATION CONTEXT (shows the user's writing preferences and interactions):
 argument. "The primary deliverable of Aim 1 is not a finding but a framework" is the most direct version of what you've been trying to say across several revisions — it names the distinction explicitly rather than implying it. "How EEG-based sleep spindle disruption, actigraphy-derived circadian fragmentation, and resting-state heart rate variability behave in relation to one another longitudinally" is doing something the earlier drafts weren't: it defines the framework's content, not just its existence, which makes it feel like a real scientific object rather than a hedge against failure.

One thing to verify: is "multi-visit polysomnography paired with separate actigraphy protocols" an accurate characterization of current clinical practice for longitudinal biosignature data in your target population, or is the actual workaround something different? If a reviewer from a sleep medicine background reads that and thinks "that's not quite right," it could undermine the credibility of the contrast. You know this literature better than I do — is that the specific incumbent, or should we name something else?

[Message #28 — user]
Okay. I think this is actually there. The line about 'more individual signals than it has ways of reading them together' — I keep coming back to it, and that's a good sign. And the independence framing at the end, 'build from, refine against, or redirect in response to,' that's exactly the kind of language that tells a study section this team has thought about failure modes without being defensive about them. That's hard to write and it's working.

One small thing I'll flag just for the revision pass, not because it's breaking anything: 'polysomnography' and 'actigraphy protocols' appear right next to each other in that long appositive and there's no soft landing for a reviewer who isn't a sleep researcher. I know we've been naming things specifically — and we should — but one parenthetical, even just '(overnight sleep monitoring)' after polysomnography, might be the difference between an engineering reviewer nodding along and quietly losing the thread. It's a minor fix and I don't want it to disturb anything else. But let's make sure we're not assuming familiarity with clinical sleep methodology from people who came up through sensors or population health. Otherwise — I think this aim is ready to move forward.

